### =============================================================================
### Foundry Hosted Agents — Multi-Customer Isolation Scenarios
### =============================================================================
### Showcases the 2-key isolation matrix from
### https://ankitbko.github.io/blog/2026/05/hosted-agents-part-2/
### through the demo proxy at backend/server.py.
###
### USAGE
### -----
### 1. Start the backend:    ./start.sh
### 2. Open this file in VS Code with the "REST Client" extension
###    (humao.rest-client) and click "Send Request" above each block.
### 3. NO copy/paste required. Multi-step scenarios chain via REST Client
###    request variables: a `# @name X` block exposes its JSON response as
###    `{{X.response.body.<jsonpath>}}` to later requests in this file.
###    `/api/chat` returns SSE (not parseable), so each scenario follows
###    its first POST with a `GET /api/history` (named e.g. `histA1`) that
###    returns a JSON `{ session_id, ... }`. The follow-up POST then sends
###    `"session_id": "{{histA1.response.body.session_id}}"` automatically.
###    Just click Send Request top-to-bottom within a scenario.
###
### ALL responses are SSE (text/event-stream). Look for these landmark events:
###   event: meta            ← what the proxy is about to send to Foundry
###   event: session         ← Foundry's agent_session_id (capture this!)
###   data: {"type":"response.completed", ...}  ← end of turn
###
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Variables — edit @host if your proxy runs on a different port.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@host = http://localhost:8080
@contentType = application/json

### Health check — confirm proxy is up.
GET {{host}}/api/health

### Show the live customer + user roster the proxy knows about.
GET {{host}}/api/customers

### Show the proxy config (Foundry endpoint, agent name, api version).
GET {{host}}/api/config


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO A — Same person continues a chat (session resumption)
### =============================================================================
### Story: Alice asks two questions in the same private thread. The platform
### must resume the same workspace and the agent must have prior context.
###
### Expected: Step 2 returns the SAME agent_session_id as step 1.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### A.1 — Alice plants a tag
# @name A1
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "Plant tag ATLAS-7 in this conversation."
}

### A.1b — Look up A.1's session_id from the proxy log (JSON, chainable)
# @name histA1
GET {{host}}/api/history?customer=contoso&user=alice&thread=thread-1&share_mode=private

### A.2 — Alice follows up using the SAME thread + auto-resolved session_id
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "session_id": "{{histA1.response.body.session_id}}",
  "message": "What was my previous message? Quote it verbatim."
}
### Look for: same agent_session_id in the response → session resumed.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO B — Cross-user (same tenant) — sessions diverge
### =============================================================================
### Story: Two coworkers at the same customer (Alice + Bob at Contoso) chat
### in private threads with the same name. They must NOT see each other's data.
###
### Expected: Bob's chat-key includes his user id, so it differs from Alice's.
### Bob gets a fresh session; the agent has no knowledge of Alice's tag.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### B.1 — Alice plants a tag in her own private thread-1
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "Plant tag BLUE-44."
}
### Note her chat-key from `event: meta`: contoso-alice-…

### B.2 — Bob (same tenant!) opens his own private thread-1
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "bob",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "What tag did the previous message in this conversation mention?"
}
### Bob's chat-key: contoso-bob-… (different from Alice's).
### Different agent_session_id, no shared history. ✅ Cross-user isolation.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO C — Cross-tenant — total isolation
### =============================================================================
### Story: Two completely different customers use the same agent. Even
### identical thread names must produce isolated workspaces.
###
### Expected: Both isolation keys differ; sessions can never cross tenants.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### C.1 — Alice@Contoso plants a tag
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "Plant tag CONTOSO-NORTH."
}

### C.2 — Carol@Fabrikam opens a thread with the same name
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "fabrikam",
  "user": "carol",
  "thread": "thread-1",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "What tag was mentioned in the previous turn?"
}
### user-key changes (user-alice → user-carol).
### chat-key changes (contoso-alice-… → fabrikam-carol-…).
### Fresh agent_session_id. ✅ Cross-tenant isolation.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO D — Shared team channel ✨ (the killer demo)
### =============================================================================
### Story: Alice and Bob (same tenant) collaborate in a shared #project-x
### channel. They must SEE THE SAME conversation while each user's per-user
### resources (OAuth, memory) stay private.
###
### Expected: Both produce the SAME chat-key (because shared mode omits the
### user from the derivation), so Foundry returns the SAME agent_session_id.
### user-keys still differ (so per-user memory/OAuth would be private).
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### D.1 — Alice posts in shared #project-x
# @name D1
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "channel-projectx",
  "share_mode": "shared",
  "message": "Hi team, this is Alice. Topic: evaluating Foundry hosted agents."
}

### D.1b — Resolve D.1's session_id from history (shared scope is keyed by chat-key,
###        so Bob will see the same session_id in his own history lookup too).
# @name histD1
GET {{host}}/api/history?customer=contoso&user=alice&thread=channel-projectx&share_mode=shared

### D.2 — Bob (same tenant) joins the SAME shared channel — session_id auto-filled
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "bob",
  "thread": "channel-projectx",
  "share_mode": "shared",
  "session_id": "{{histD1.response.body.session_id}}",
  "message": "This is Bob joining. What did Alice say in the previous message?"
}
### Bob's chat-key MATCHES Alice's: contoso-shared-…
### Bob's user-key DIFFERS from Alice's: user-bob vs user-alice.
### Same agent_session_id reused. ✅ Teams-channel pattern.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO E — Shared channel + cross-tenant — still isolated
### =============================================================================
### Story: Contoso and Fabrikam both have a channel called #project-x.
### Even in shared mode, the platform must keep them apart — competitors
### can't snoop just by guessing channel names.
###
### Expected: Backend namespaces shared chat-keys by tenant prefix, so
### contoso-shared-… ≠ fabrikam-shared-…. Different sessions.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### E.1 — Alice@Contoso in shared #project-x
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "channel-projectx",
  "share_mode": "shared",
  "message": "Note: Contoso's tag is PROJ-ALPHA-9."
}

### E.2 — Carol@Fabrikam in shared #project-x (same channel name!)
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "fabrikam",
  "user": "carol",
  "thread": "channel-projectx",
  "share_mode": "shared",
  "message": "What tag was mentioned in the previous turn of this channel?"
}
### Different chat-keys (contoso-shared-… vs fabrikam-shared-…).
### Different agent_session_id. ✅ Multi-tenant safety even for shared chats.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO F — Default-scope vs explicit chat-key
### =============================================================================
### Story: When the proxy sends NO x-ms-chat-isolation-key header at all,
### Foundry falls back to a default scope derived from the user-key alone.
### This default scope is its own partition — invisible to requests that
### DO send a chat-key, and vice versa.
###
### Expected: Two requests from the same user to the same thread name —
### one with `omit_chat_key:true`, one without — produce DIFFERENT sessions.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### F.1 — Alice WITHOUT chat-key (default scope)
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-2",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "omit_chat_key": true,
  "message": "Hi from the default scope. Tag: SCOPE-DEFAULT-1."
}
### Inspect `event: meta`: chat_key is null, chat_key_omitted is true.

### F.2 — Same Alice, same thread, but NOW with explicit chat-key
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-2",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "Now with chat-key. What tag was mentioned in the previous turn?"
}
### Different agent_session_id from F.1 — the explicit chat-key partition is
### independent from the default scope. ✅ "No chat-key" is its own world.


### =============================================================================
### SCENARIO G — Session-id mismatch (experimental)
### =============================================================================
### Story: A malicious user obtains another user's agent_session_id and
### tries to resume that session under their own keys. Per the blog the
### platform should reject the attempt — chat-key is the actual gate.
###
### NOTE: Foundry's behaviour for the `agent_session_id` field on POST
### /endpoint/protocols/openai/responses depends on platform version. The
### blog demonstrates 403 on GET /sessions/{id} with a wrong key (see G.3).
### POST may silently assign a fresh session, return the same id, or 403.
### -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### G.1 — Alice creates a session in a private thread
# @name G1
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "alice",
  "thread": "thread-secret",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "message": "Establish this session. Tag: ALICE-SECRET-42."
}

### G.1b — Resolve Alice's session_id (so G.2 can attempt to spoof it as Bob)
# @name histG1
GET {{host}}/api/history?customer=contoso&user=alice&thread=thread-secret&share_mode=private

### G.2 — Bob tries to resume Alice's session id under HIS own keys (auto-filled)
POST {{host}}/api/chat
Content-Type: {{contentType}}

{
  "customer": "contoso",
  "user": "bob",
  "thread": "thread-secret",
  "share_mode": "private",
  "session_id": "{{histG1.response.body.session_id}}",
  "message": "What tag did the previous turn mention?"
}
### Either Foundry assigns Bob a different session, returns an error event,
### or (depending on platform behaviour) silently honours the id without
### actually granting access to the conversation history.

### G.3 — Verify isolation via the SESSIONS LIST endpoint (more deterministic)
###   Listing sessions with Bob's keys should NOT include Alice's session id.
GET {{host}}/api/sessions?customer=contoso&user=bob&thread=thread-secret&share_mode=private

###   Listing sessions with Alice's keys SHOULD include it.
GET {{host}}/api/sessions?customer=contoso&user=alice&thread=thread-secret&share_mode=private


### =============================================================================
### Quick reference — what the proxy derives for each (customer, user, mode, thread)
### =============================================================================
###
###   user-key  = "user-<user>"                       (per end-user)
###
###   chat-key (private) = "<customer>-<user>-<sha256(customer:user:thread)[:24]>"
###     → unique per (tenant, user, thread) — Alice's "Thread 1" ≠ Bob's "Thread 1"
###
###   chat-key (shared)  = "<customer>-shared-<sha256(customer:thread)[:24]>"
###     → unique per (tenant, thread) — same across all users in that tenant
###       (Teams-channel pattern), but still namespaced by tenant.
###
###   omit_chat_key=true → no x-ms-chat-isolation-key header at all.
###     → platform uses a default scope derived from user-key. This is its own
###       partition, separate from any explicit chat-key partition.
